Cerknica Thumb () is a small glacitectal trough just northwest of Krivi Lošinj in the Kvarnerić archipelago of the northern Adriatic Sea. The name of the feature locally is Kaše. It is one of many such features () in the northern Adriatic, and in particular in the vicinity of the islands of Krk and Cres.

Geography
The Cerknica Thumb is the westernmost of a group of such features, the others being the (from north to south):

Mešteto Thumb - close to the town of Senj;
Lovrecina Thumb - in the fjord-like bay of Žut mountain range near the town of Opatija;
Dragon's Throat - in the vicinity of the settlement of Murter, located on the northwestern coast of the island of Murter, in the central part of the Croatian part of the Adriatic;
Cerknica Thumb - (the topic of the present article).
The features are similar in dimensions, shape, and orientation in the eastern-to-western direction. The combined area of all these features exceeds 10 square kilometers.
